# Use Bun

This project uses **Bun** for dependency management and backend/runtime scripts. Do not use npm, yarn, or pnpm unless the user explicitly asks.

## Package management

```bash
# Install dependencies
bun install

# Add / remove packages
bun add <package>
bun add -d <package>
bun remove <package>
```

## Running scripts

```bash
# Prefer bun run for package.json scripts
bun run start
bun run lint
bun run build-frontend

# Direct Bun execution for backend entrypoints
bun run app.ts
bun --watch --env-file=.env app.ts
```

## Rules

- Use `bun.lock` as the lockfile source of truth — never generate or commit `package-lock.json`, `yarn.lock`, or `pnpm-lock.yaml`.
- When installing or updating dependencies, use `bun add` / `bun remove`, not `npm install` or `npx`.
- When running project scripts in the terminal, use `bun run <script>`, not `npm run <script>`.
- The backend and workers run on Bun (`bun run app.ts`, `bun run ./backend/workers/index.ts`).
- Frontend dev/build still uses Next.js via existing scripts; invoke them through `bun run`, not npm.

## Avoid

```bash
npm install
npm run lint
npx some-package
yarn add foo
pnpm add foo
```
